public class Solution {
    public boolean isPowerOfThree(int n) {
        if (n <= 0) {
            return false;
        }
        while (n % 3 == 0) {
            n /= 3;
        }
        return n == 1;
    }
}
```

However, this solution is not the most efficient as it uses a loop.

A more efficient solution without loops/recursion is to use the property of logarithms that states log_b(a) = c if and only if b^c = a. 

Here's a Java solution using this property:

```java
public class Solution {
    public boolean isPowerOfThree(int n) {
        if (n <= 0) {
            return false;
        }
        double log = Math.log(n) / Math.log(3);
        return Math.abs(log - Math.floor(log)) < 1e-9;
    }
}
```

In this solution, we use `Math.log(n) / Math.log(3)` to calculate the logarithm of n base 3. If n is a power of three, then this expression will be an integer, and `Math.abs(log - Math.floor(log))` will be close to zero. If n is not a power of three, then this expression will not be an integer, and `Math.abs(log - Math.floor(log))` will be greater than zero. 

Note that we use `Math.abs(log - Math.floor(log)) < 1e-9` instead of `Math.abs(log - Math.floor(log)) == 0` because of floating-point precision issues.

